## Freedom of Speech in the United States: Constitutional Limits and Court Cases

The United States is often cited as an exception due to its robust protection of free speech under the First Amendment. However, even in the U.S., **freedom of speech is not unlimited**.

### Categories of Unprotected Speech

The U.S. Supreme Court has identified categories of speech that are not protected, including:

- Obscenity
- Defamation
- Fraud
- Incitement to imminent lawless action
- Fighting words
- True threats
- Speech integral to criminal conduct
- Child pornography

For example, in *Brandenburg v. Ohio* (1969), the Court ruled that speech advocating illegal conduct is protected unless it is intended and likely to incite imminent lawless action ([Morethingsjapanese, 2021](https://morethingsjapanese.com/what-supreme-court-cases-involve-freedom-of-speech/)).

### Landmark Cases

| Case                          | Year | Significance                                            |
|-------------------------------|------|--------------------------------------------------------|
| Tinker v. Des Moines           | 1969 | Affirmed student free speech rights in schools         |
| Chaplinsky v. New Hampshire    | 1942 | Established "fighting words" doctrine                   |
| New York Times Co. v. Sullivan | 1964 | Protected press against defamation claims               |
| Cohen v. California            | 1971 | Protected offensive speech                               |

These cases illustrate the nuanced approach the Court takes in balancing free speech with societal interests.

